 Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Breherval, Eure, Normandy, France":"Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk","England":"England","Ivry La Bataille, Eure, Normandy, France":"Ivry-la-Bataille, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Bec Abbey, Eure, Le Bec-Hellouin, Haute-Normandy, France":"Le Bec-Hellouin, Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"–1079":"–1079","1050–1115":"1050–1115","1065–1116":"1065–1116","–1050":"–1050","before 1050/1060":"before 1050","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1050":"1050","980":"0980","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","994":"0994","1079":"1079","1035":"1035","1002":"1002","before 1065":"before 1065","from 1066 to 1089":"from 1066 to 1089","Ivry-la-Bataille, Normandy, France":"Ivry-la-Bataille, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","Breherval, Eure, Normandy, France":"Eure, Normandy, France","England":"England","Ivry La Bataille, Eure, Normandy, France":"Ivry-la-Bataille, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","France":"France","Bec Abbey, Eure, Le Bec-Hellouin, Haute-Normandy, France":"Le Bec-Hellouin, Eure, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705176,"age":19,"year":"0980","julianDay":2078998,"title":"Vikings Invade England","description":"Viking raiders from Scandinavia invaded England in 980. Years later in 991, the English government paid them 10,000 in hopes for peace. The Viking raiders, however, continued to force more money from England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705177,"age":33,"year":"0994","julianDay":2084112,"title":"Danes Attack London","description":"Danes and Norwegians attacked London unsuccessfully in 994.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_London#10th_century_London","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Anglo-Saxon London","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705178,"age":41,"year":"1002","julianDay":2087033,"title":"St. Brice's Day Massacre","description":"King Aethelred ordered all Danish men in England to be killed. It is unknown how many Danes were killed due to this order.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705181,"age":74,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":105,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Roger d'Ivry was born in Eure, Normandy, France as the son of Robert d'Ivry. He had at least 1 son with Hildeburge Gallardon. In 1066, his occup